**** How to migrate etcd from http to https ****

1: Create etcd Server Key
# openssl genrsa -out etcd-server.key 4096

2: Create CSR

# openssl req -new -key etcd-server.key -subj "/CN=etcd" -out etcd-server.csr

3: Create SAN File

Very important.
cat > etcd-server.cnf <<EOF
subjectAltName = IP:127.0.0.1,DNS:localhost
EOF

4: Sign Certificate Using Existing CA
# openssl x509 -req \
  -in etcd-server.csr \
  -CA ca.crt \
  -CAkey ca.key \
  -CAcreateserial \
  -out etcd-server.crt \
  -days 3650 \
  -extfile etcd-server.cnf

5. Result

You now have:

etcd-server.crt
etcd-server.key


6. Copy Certificates

Example:

cp ca.crt /var/lib/etcd/
cp etcd-server.crt /var/lib/etcd/
cp etcd-server.key /var/lib/etcd/
cp kube-api-server.crt /var/lib/etcd/
cp kube-api-server.key /var/lib/etcd/

7 — Modify etcd Service

Find etcd service:

systemctl cat etcd

or:

cat /etc/systemd/system/etcd.service
Change These Lines

FROM:

--listen-client-urls=http://127.0.0.1:2379
--advertise-client-urls=http://127.0.0.1:2379

TO:
--listen-client-urls=https://127.0.0.1:2379
--advertise-client-urls=https://127.0.0.1:2379

Add TLS Parameters

Add these:
--cert-file=/var/lib/etcd/etcd-server.crt
--key-file=/var/lib/etcd/etcd-server.key
--trusted-ca-file=/var/lib/etcd/ca.crt
--client-cert-auth=true

8: Restart etcd
systemctl daemon-reload
systemctl restart etcd

systemctl status etcd

9: Test etcd TLS

Export variables:

export ETCDCTL_API=3
export ETCDCTL_CACERT=/var/lib/etcd/ca.crt
export ETCDCTL_CERT=/var/lib/etcd/kube-api-server.crt
export ETCDCTL_KEY=/var/lib/etcd/kube-api-server.key

Test:
# etcdctl \
  --endpoints=https://127.0.0.1:2379 \
  endpoint health

Expected:

https://127.0.0.1:2379 is healthy
Step 6 — Modify kube-apiserver

10: Edit kube-apiserver systemd service.

Change:

--etcd-servers=http://127.0.0.1:2379

TO:

--etcd-servers=https://127.0.0.1:2379
Add These Parameters
--etcd-cafile=/var/lib/etcd/ca.crt

--etcd-certfile=/var/lib/etcd/kube-api-server.crt

--etcd-keyfile=/var/lib/etcd/kube-api-server.key
Final API Server Config
--etcd-servers=https://127.0.0.1:2379
--etcd-cafile=/var/lib/etcd/ca.crt
--etcd-certfile=/var/lib/etcd/kube-api-server.crt
--etcd-keyfile=/var/lib/etcd/kube-api-server.key
Step 7 — Restart API Server
systemctl restart kube-apiserver

systemctl status kube-apiserver
Step 8 — Verify Cluster

# kubectl get nodes

If nodes appear:

TLS migration successful

Very Important Understanding

You are using:

kube-api-server.crt

as:

etcd client certificate

This is acceptable because:

it is signed by same CA
etcd trusts that CA
mutual TLS succeeds
Architecture After Migration
kube-apiserver
     |
     | HTTPS + mTLS
     |
     v
etcd
Best Practice in Production

Usually production creates:

apiserver-etcd-client.crt

separately instead of reusing kube-api-server.crt.

But for learning/lab:

Reusing kube-api-server cert is fine
Most Important Learning

To enable secure etcd communication you need:

etcd HTTPS listener
trusted CA
client certificate authentication
API server TLS configuration
matching CA trust on both sides
